segments.text: Okay, this is May the 6th, 1990, interview by Michael Enochs.
The person being interviewed is Alan Enochs.
And Alan, the first question is, in the interest of accumulated knowledge, asking you to donate this tape.
the Texas A&M oral history collection in the University Archives.
Is that all right with you?
That's okay.
Okay.
All right.
Now then, first question.
You joined the Army in 1967, and I have here specifically to become a warrant officer to fly helicopters and to go to Vietnam.
And what were your reasons for this decision?
I needed to get drafted.
As I was out of school or not doing well in school, I figured my draft number was about up, and so it was time to make the best deal.
But also, it was a shortcut to go and start flying.
So there were really two reasons.
Yeah, flying the helicopters was really the main reason.
Vietnam was not something you were necessarily interested in, if possible.
Is that correct?
Or were you wanting to go to Vietnam?
Not at all.
OK. No, that was one of the unfortunate.
It was sort of inevitable at that point.
Exact consequences of doing it.
All right.
OK. After arriving in Vietnam, can you describe your assignments and activities?

Arriving in Vietnam, I went to 17th Group and was assigned to 7th and 17th Air Cavalry and became a scout pilot for them, which was basically going out, flying out, hovering in the bushes, looking for any signs of any enemy activity in any suspected hotspots wherever we were put.
And we usually found them by getting shot at, but that's what we did.
Okay, uh, where were you stationed at that time?
I was stationed in Campanari in, uh, Pleiku, Vietnam.
Pleiku.
And shortly thereafter went to Phanthiet.
To, uh, would you repeat that?
Uh, went to Phanthiet, Vietnam.
I spent, uh, five months in Phanthiet, went to, back to Campanari, and then our troops moved to Bamituid, and then I went back to Campanari at the end of the tour.
Okay.
Uh,
Would you describe the racial makeup of your group?
Mostly white.
Enlisted, probably a few more blacks.
Officers, probably 2% to 3% were black.
As far as enlisted, I really can't remember how many there were.
But it might have been 10% to 20% black.
Okay.
Now, of the 2% or 3% officers that were black, were part of these also pilots?
Oh, yeah.
The unit I was with was mainly pilots.
There were 67 officers in the unit, and probably 66 of them were officers, pilots.
Okay, and of the 66, maybe a couple, as many as two or three of them were black?
Uh-huh.
Yeah, I was just trying to think how many there were, and it was one or two of them.
Okay.
I remember one of them real well, but I can't remember half the truth anyway.
Yeah, I understand.
Were there any racial problems within the group?
None at all that I remember.
Okay.
No, I don't remember any racial problems.
What were your feelings about the U.S. involvement in Vietnam when you joined?
Really, no feelings.
I was 19 years old when I joined.
As far as should be there or shouldn't be there, I guess that's where you're just trusting in the government.
So, I guess
It was okay at that time with me.
During your first tour of duty, did your feelings regarding our involvement change any?
Did my feelings change any?
I'm just trying to think of how I felt when I came out.

and uh yeah i guess though i still wasn't uh against so no no i still wasn't against the war at that point you still felt like that what the country was doing they were doing for a good reason yeah uh
Was there any discussion within your group about why we were fighting in Vietnam?
Very little.
I really, like I say, it's a long time ago, but I don't really remember any heated discussions or anything going on about why we were there.
Okay.
I've got here if any.
of this discussion, or did any of this discussion change between your first tour of duty in 1969 and when you were over there the second time?
Second tour, I don't really remember anything much, but when I was there, second tour, I was only in the unit for just over a month, it seems like.
I think like I was in, I know I got out in January of 71, but I got there

November and it was a lot of hard November when I got assigned to a unit so I was it was maybe a little more than a month I was actually in unit I didn't really hardly get to know people well I don't have this question on the sheet but let me ask you this between the time you got back from your first terror duty while you were
between tours of duty, and I guess you were stationed in Germany a good part of that time.
Was there any discussion?
Do you recall any discussion about our involvement in Vietnam between those people that were in with you?
No, I really don't.
No, I don't remember any discussion at all in Germany.
OK.
Could you describe your relationship with the Vietnamese people, both the military personnel and the civilians?

Okay, I was very isolated from the Vietnamese people totally in the unit as we were, from the time I got in the country, we were always restricted in going into town, or more or less always, and so I had very little chance to ever
mix or talk with any of the Vietnamese people.

Say the last three months that I was in country and I was the civil affairs officer for the squadron that I was in, which meant that I had two villages, a mountain yard village named and a Vietnamese village, Lausanne, that we had a civil affairs team that would go out to
It helped out with little government projects.
We also rent a medical shelter in Lausanne.
And then I also took care of the indigenous personnel on the base.
But any in-depth discussions, didn't really have any.
It was on a... Oh, what?
Very shallow level.
It was...
Just business-type relationships, you might say.
Okay.
Did your feelings toward the people of Vietnam change while you were there?
For instance, your feelings toward the military personnel?
I didn't really feel like... Well, I guess that was one of the feelings over there, was the fact that we just didn't feel like they cared much about...
They didn't have their hearts into the fighting end of it, that might be a good way to put it.

they uh anytime they've gotten any heavy firefighters or something they were always calling for u.s assistance and so we would be rolling in to help them out on something like that but they never really appeared to be good fighters or fighting for a cause or anything you might say and your uh experience there with the civilians during the last
three months, could you describe possibly how you felt about their feelings towards Americans or whatever?
Their feelings towards Americans?
The Vietnamese, the people of Lausanne, were
Oh, they were nice enough, but they didn't really give a hoot about us being there.
Where the mountain yards were more, were happier to be around the American people.
They were a little more congenial.
As far as working with you and your efforts to whatever you were doing there, were they
Did they work with you on it, or just exactly as far as that part went, a working relationship?
The mountain yards were a lot more to kick in and help and whatever, where the Vietnamese people were really, I guess, looking for a handout.
You know, come in, do this, do that, do that.
That will help us.
It's fine.
Could you describe the general attitudes of the Americans that you knew in Vietnam toward the Vietnamese military?
The general attitude was that they didn't fight worth a hoot.
They weren't...
You wouldn't trust them to help you on some job as far as fire fighting or whatever.
Yeah, that's sort of the general feeling, sort of what I said before.
They just did not care to contribute that much or weren't able to, whatever.
Okay.
How about towards the civilians?
The general attitude of the people you were with or the Americans?
general attitude, I guess we weren't that well accepted in Vietnam.
Okay.
While in Vietnam, were you aware of the peace movement in the United States?
Yes.
While there, could you describe your feelings towards that movement?
Well, it wasn't very good.
I guess
or while there, yeah, it just didn't feel like you had any support from the U.S. at all.
Was there discussion within the group as far as about the issues that were brought up by the movement?
I really can't recall any feelings or any discussions.
Lost my place.
While performing your duties, were there any restrictions or limitations in place because of politics?
And did the nature of these restrictions or limitations change, for instance, between your first tour of duty and your second tour of duty?
There were a lot of limitations on like rules of engagement.
They were fairly strict, even on the first tour, where any time we went into an area, we were given room to engage in the first tour.
We were actually given free fire zones sometimes.
But if it wasn't a free fire zone, even if we were being shot at before we could return fire, we would have to request permission to return fire and have
somebody approve it.
Second tour, it was very, very strict that you could get in a bind really if you didn't know the person who approved the shoot.
So, and generally politics played in it.
I would surmise as some of the areas that, like second tour, one of the areas I was in
I was flying with the 23rd Infantry Division, which was originally the Americal Division, as William Kelly's name.
And we were up close to the village of Milai.
Had a bird shot down.
I was on station in a Cobra at that time with one gun, fully loaded, and requested permission to fire.
And we couldn't shoot back, even though we were being shot at that time with a bird on the ground.

had to get him out the best we could so and they kept saying no civilians on the ground and it was the area that we were in pure reason that we couldn't shoot back yeah so it was just just strictly because you were close to an area that had already gotten a lot of attention exactly yeah but uh generally there was a lot of areas that you could shoot in that were
areas of suspected heavy enemy concentration that you weren't allowed to shoot in just because you weren't allowed to shoot there.
Right.
That didn't work.
Okay.
And your incident there near Malai, Malai, you're talking about having a bird on the ground, and I'm assuming there were men on the ground that you were trying to... Oh, yeah, yeah.
We had a bird shot down, so we had...
It was a Huey.
We had...
Probably eight to ten of our own on the ground.
Seems like we used to carry about four to six birds, so yeah, six to eight people on the ground.
Okay, and wound up other helicopters going in under fire?
Yeah.
But not able to fire while they were going in?
Well, supposedly not able to.
Okay.
Officially not able to.
Officially not able to.
Okay.
Could you describe your feelings about how the military was conducting the war in Vietnam?
I don't know.
As far as the tactics that were being used, I don't know.
At the time, I sure was in a position to understand the overall strategies and
No, I really don't know how I felt about it.

Well, when you were, for instance, in these positions where you knew that you were in contact or you had contact with the enemy, but you're not being allowed to either return fire or to pursue the enemy, did that lead to discussion between your men as to why or what the purpose was?
Yeah, everybody was generally very upset about the whole situation.
Was not pleased at all.
But what do you, I don't know what to say about it.
Okay, well now, in the second part of that same question, was your feelings towards the way the U.S. government was conducting the war.
Were they doing it right?
Were they doing it wrong?
I really don't know.
I don't know if they were handling it right or not.
It was a guerrilla war.
It's a new type of war.
No lines, nothing.
How do you know if you're winning or losing or whatever?
I never really had much feeling on it.
Things were getting ahead if there was something to do different and right.
Sort of felt like we weren't doing that much.
Okay, well, now then, when you returned to the United States, could you describe your welcome, if any?
Welcome is a bad word to use for it.
Yeah, you came back and you just didn't want to wear the uniform.
You didn't want to be recognized as part of the military because you were not treated well.
I don't know.
More or less abused if you had the uniform on would be a good way to put it.
When you came back your first time, where did you come in?
Came into, well, when I came back first time, I came into Washington.
planted in Tacoma.
Okay.
Uh, and, uh, did you, did you experience this feeling or this attitude about not wanting to wear the uniform right off or was it something?
Yeah, generally, uh, anybody around, I'd say anybody, most people or a lot of people you ran into were, um,
Oh, gosh, what the word.
Well, you didn't get a good welcome.
Hey, great job or anything.
You never heard anything like that.
What are you all doing over there anyway?
War mongers.
I don't know.
Gentle attitude was not good.
Since you're from the middle of the country, this...
Did this seem to change any as you, for instance, got home in Oklahoma as opposed to on the coast?
Yes.
You didn't have near the animosity that you felt on the coast that you did at home.
But it wouldn't necessarily still describe it as a welcome other than with your family.
Yeah, that's true.
Family and friends, of course, welcome you home.
Right.
Some people were curious and would ask, but you didn't really.
There is no other welcome besides that.
This great job thing you mentioned just didn't turn up very often.
No, not at all.
Okay.
After you returned to the States, did you feel you had to explain your reasons for going to Vietnam or your actions while you were there?
Sort of just avoided the subject.
I tried not to explain too much because you sort of ended up on the losing end of any battle that you got into.
If nothing else, by sheer numbers of people that were talking to you, unless you were one-on-one, but I don't know.
Yeah, you maybe felt a little guilty or whatever about going.
Okay.
Did you feel the...
that the citizens' attitudes about the war were informed, or were they, for instance, tired of the whole thing, or avoiding the whole issue because of some hidden guilt of their own?
The media informed everybody every day.
I think people were tired of the war, and they wanted to see it over.
It was enough for nothing else to quit seeing it on the news every night.
They definitely got an upfront view.
from what I saw on the news.
Yeah, it was.
We had the running statistic of the daily body count and all of this.
And I don't know what all it seemed, as I recall, every night.
So maybe that, like I say, the people, they were just too busy with their own lives to even listen maybe.
about the questions of the whys of the Vietnam War?
Yeah, I don't know how informed the people were.
Like I said, I talked to very few people, really, about Vietnam.
I sort of tried to avoid the issue, as a matter of fact.
Okay.
All right, now then, the last question that we have is the biggie.
And this is, do you recall the songs that were played in Vietnam?
And...
Were they important to you because of what they reminded you of, or were they important because of the way they reflected, or because they reflected the way you felt at the time?
The song I remember the biggest is Country Joe and the Fish, singing, oh, send your boy off to Vietnam.
I can't remember the name of the song.
But I get, I don't know, we had a lot of,
thongs that you heard, it was just sort of a release mechanism to, uh, because you were scared to use.
So I, I don't know.
I remember you're going home in the body bag and I remember the country Joe and the fish song.
Um, guys, I remember the thongs that were over there.
I remember the hair, uh,
The play here was out and we had the soundtrack to that.
You heard that a lot.
But as far as identifying with all the feelings of the songs and so forth, I can't really remember any songs that we clung onto at all.
As far as, well, I guess there was a lot of songs against the war at that time, against war period,
that I don't really remember any that I can find on to.
Okay, well, that is all the questions that I had at this time.
And is there anything else you can think of that you might want to add?
No.
All right, well, Alan, I appreciate it.
Okay.
And...
